# Agentic Game Dev

Agentic Game Dev coordinates a small team of AI agents to design, implement, review, and refine a complete Pygame game. Version 2 replaces the original 2024 single-script prototype with a package that is safer to run, easier to test, and much better at keeping multiple generated files coherent.

## What changed

- Designer and architect agents explore the brief in parallel.
- A lead architect produces a schema-validated build contract with exact file APIs.
- One implementation agent owns each file.
- An integration reviewer repairs syntax, imports, gameplay logic, and polish issues.
- Generated filenames are allow-listed and cannot escape the output directory.
- Existing output is preserved unless --replace is explicit; repositories and the current directory are never replacement targets.
- Generated code is not executed unless --run is explicit.
- Every build gets static parsing and a headless import smoke test.
- The model, renderer, output path, timeouts, and repair budget are visible CLI options.
- The old destructive import-time behavior and fragile XML/regex parsing are gone.

The generated game uses procedural Pygame visuals and audio, so it remains self-contained. Choose --renderer moderngl when the brief genuinely benefits from shaders.

## Setup

Python 3.11 or newer is recommended.

~~~powershell
python -m venv .venv
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
python -m pip install -e .
Copy-Item .env.example .env
~~~

Open .env and replace the placeholder API key:

~~~dotenv
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your-anthropic-api-key
ANTHROPIC_MODEL=claude-sonnet-5
~~~

The .env file is ignored by Git. Do not commit real API keys. The model entry is optional; omit it to use the built-in default.

## Create a game

~~~powershell
agent-game-dev create "A neon arena game where movement paints temporary walls"
~~~

The default output is generated_game. Review it first, then run it:

~~~powershell
python generated_game\main.py
~~~

To replace a previous generated game and launch it after validation:

~~~powershell
agent-game-dev --output generated_game create --replace --run "Your game brief"
~~~

Global options go before create or refine:

~~~text
--model MODEL
--output DIRECTORY
--renderer pygame|moderngl
--repair-attempts N
--smoke-timeout SECONDS
~~~

The CLI prints the effective settings before making API calls, so cost and behavior are not hidden.

## Refine after playtesting

~~~powershell
agent-game-dev --output generated_game refine "The first minute is too easy and hits need stronger feedback"
~~~

Refinement can only replace Python files already in that generated project. It cannot invent paths or write elsewhere.

## Safety

This program writes model-generated source code. It constrains where agents can write, scans syntax, imports the project with dummy SDL drivers, and requires --run before launching it. Those controls reduce risk; they do not prove arbitrary generated code is safe. Read generated files before running games made from untrusted prompts, and use an isolated environment for serious experimentation.

## Development

~~~powershell
python -m unittest discover -s tests -v
python -m compileall -q agentic_game_dev tests agent_game_maker.py
~~~

The provider adapter, orchestration, workspace policy, and validation are separate modules so they can be tested or replaced independently.
